# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: botanical-name
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] The **ABC model of flower development** is a scientific model of the process by which flowering plants produce a pattern of gene expression in meristems that leads to the appearance of an organ oriented towards sexual reproduction, a flower.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] The latter phase has been modelled using the **ABC model**, which aims to describe the biological basis of the process from the perspective of molecular and developmental genetics.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] An external stimulus is required in order to trigger the differentiation of the meristem into a flower meristem.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] This stimulus will activate mitotic cell division in the apical meristem, particularly on its sides where new primordia are formed.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] This same stimulus will also cause the meristem to follow a developmental pattern that will lead to the growth of floral meristems as opposed to vegetative meristems.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] The main difference between these two types of meristem, apart from the obvious disparity between the objective organ, is the verticillate (or whorled) phyllotaxis, that is, the absence of stem elongation among the successive whorls or verticils of the primordium.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] These verticils follow an acropetal development, giving rise to sepals, petals, stamens and carpels.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] Another difference from vegetative axillary meristems is that the floral meristem is "determined", which means that, once differentiated, its cells will no longer divide.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] The identity of the organs present in the four floral verticils is a consequence of the interaction of at least three types of gene products, each with distinct functions.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] According to the ABC model, functions A and C are required in order to determine the identity of the verticils of the perianth and the reproductive verticils, respectively.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] These functions are exclusive and the absence of one of them means that the other will determine the identity of all the floral verticils.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] The B function allows the differentiation of petals from sepals in the secondary verticil, as well as the differentiation of the stamen from the carpel on the tertiary verticil.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] Goethe's **foliar theory** was formulated in the 18th century and it suggests that the constituent parts of a flower are structurally modified leaves, which are functionally specialized for reproduction or protection.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] The transition from the vegetative phase to a reproductive phase involves a dramatic change in the plant's vital cycle, perhaps the most important one, as the process must be carried out correctly in order to guarantee that the plant produces descendants.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] This transition is characterised by the induction and development of the meristem of the inflorescence, which will produce a collection of flowers or one flower.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] This morphogenetic change contains both endogenous and exogenous elements: For example, in order for the change to be initiated the plant must have a certain number of leaves and contain a certain level of total biomass.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] Certain environmental conditions are also required such as a characteristic photoperiod.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] Plant hormones play an important part in the process, with the gibberellins having a particularly important role.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] There are many signals that regulate the molecular biology of the process.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] The following three genes in *Arabidopsis thaliana* possess both common and independent functions in floral transition: *FLOWERING LOCUS T* (*FT*), *LEAFY* (*LFY*), *SUPPRESSOR OF OVEREXPRESSION OF CONSTANS1* (*SOC1*, also called *AGAMOUS-LIKE20*).
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] *SOC1* is a MADS-box-type gene, which integrates responses to photoperiod, vernalization and gibberellins.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] The meristem can be defined as the tissue or group of plant tissues that contain undifferentiated stem cells, which are capable of producing any type of cell tissue.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] Their maintenance and development, both in the vegetative meristem or the meristem of the inflorescence is controlled by genetic cell fate determination mechanisms.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] This means that a number of genes will directly regulate, for example, the maintenance of the stem cell's characteristics (gene *WUSCHEL* or *WUS*), and others will act via negative feedback mechanisms in order to inhibit a characteristic (gene *CLAVATA* or *CLV*).
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] In this way both mechanisms give rise to a feedback loop, which along with other elements lend a great deal of robustness to the system.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] Along with the *WUS* gene the *SHOOTMERISTEMLESS* (*STM*) gene also represses the differentiation of the meristematic dome.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] This gene acts by inhibiting the possible differentiation of the stem cells but still allows cell division in the daughter cells, which, had they been allowed to differentiate, would have given rise to distinct organs.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] A flower's anatomy, as defined by the presence of a series of organs (sepals, petals, stamens and carpels) positioned according to a given pattern, facilitate sexual reproduction in flowering plants.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] The ABC model of flower development was first formulated by George Haughn and Chris Somerville in 1988.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] It was first used as a model to describe the collection of genetic mechanisms that establish floral organ identity in the Rosids, as exemplified by *Arabidopsis thaliana*, and the Asterids, as demonstrated by *Antirrhinum majus*.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] Both species have four verticils (sepals, petals, stamens and carpels), which are defined by the differential expression of a number of homeotic genes present in each verticil.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] This means that the sepals are solely characterized by the expression of A genes, while the petals are characterized by the co-expression of A and B genes.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] The B and C genes establish the identity of the stamens and the carpels only require C genes to be active.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] Type A and C genes are reciprocally antagonistic.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] The fact that these homeotic genes determine an organ's identity becomes evident when a gene that represents a particular function, for example the A gene, is not expressed.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *Arabidopsis* this loss results in a flower which is composed of one verticil of carpels, another containing stamens and another of carpels.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] This method for studying gene function uses reverse genetics techniques to produce transgenic plants that contain a mechanism for gene silencing through RNA interference.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] In other studies, using forward genetics techniques such as genetic mapping, it is the analysis of the phenotypes of flowers with structural anomalies that leads to the cloning of the gene of interest.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] The flowers may possess a non-functional or over expressed allele for the gene being studied.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] The existence of two supplementary functions, D and E, have also been proposed in addition to the A, B and C functions already discussed.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] Function D specifies the identity of the ovule, as a separate reproductive function from the development of the carpels, which occurs after their determination.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] Function E relates to a physiological requirement that is a characteristic of all floral verticils, although, it was initially described as necessary for the development of the three innermost verticils (Function E *sensu stricto*).
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] However, its broader definition (*sensu lato*) suggests that it is required in the four verticils.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] The gene products of genes with D and E functions are also MADS-box genes.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] The methodology for studying flower development involves two steps.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] Firstly, the identification of the exact genes required for determining the identity of the floral meristem.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *A. thaliana* these include APETALA1 (*AP1*) and LEAFY (*LFY*).
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] Secondly, genetic analysis is carried out on the aberrant phenotypes for the relative characteristics of the flowers, which allows the characterization of the homeotic genes implicated in the process.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] There are a great many mutations that affect floral morphology, although the analysis of these mutants is a recent development.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] Supporting evidence for the existence of these mutations comes from the fact that a large number affect the identity of floral organs.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] For example, some organs develop in a location where others should develop.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] This is called homeotic mutation, which is analogous to HOX gene mutations found in *Drosophila*.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *Arabidopsis* and *Antirrhinum*, the two taxa on which models are based, these mutations always affect adjacent verticils.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] Cloning studies have been carried out on DNA in the genes associated with the affected homeotic functions in the mutants discussed above.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] These studies used serial analysis of gene expression throughout floral development to show patterns of tissue expression, which, in general, correspond with the predictions of the ABC model.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] The nature of these genes corresponds to that of transcription factors, which, as expected, have analogous structures to a group of factors contained in yeasts and animal cells.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] This group is called MADS, which is an acronym for the different factors contained in the group.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] These MADS factors have been detected in all the vegetable species studied, although the involvement of other elements involved in the regulation of gene expression cannot be discounted.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *A. thaliana*, function A is mainly represented by two genes *APETALA1* (*AP1)* and *APETALA2* (*AP2*) *AP1* is a MADS-box type gene, while *AP2* belongs to the family of genes that contains AP2, which it gives its name to and which consists of transcription factors that are only found in plants.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] AP2 has also been shown to complex with the co-repressor TOPLESS (TPL) in developing floral buds to repress the C-class gene *AGAMOUS* (*AG*).
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] *AP2* not only functions in the first two verticils, but also in the remaining two, in developing ovules and even in leaves.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] It is also likely that post-transcriptional regulation exists, which controls its A function, or even that it has other purposes in the determination of organ identity independent of that mentioned here.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *Antirrhinum*, the orthologous gene to *AP1* is *SQUAMOSA* (*SQUA*), which also has a particular impact on the floral meristem.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] The homologs for *AP2* are *LIPLESS1* (*LIP1*) and *LIPLESS2* (*LIP2*), which have a redundant function and are of special interest in the development of sepals, petals and ovules.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] A total of three genes have been isolated from *Petunia hybrida* that are similar to *AP2*: *P. hybrida APETALA2A* (*PhAP2A*), *PhAP2B* and *PhAP2C*.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] *PhAP2A* is, to a large degree, homologous with the *AP2* gene of *Arabidopsis*, both in its sequence and in its expression pattern, which suggests that the two genes are orthologs.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] The proteins *PhAP2B* and *PhAP2C*, on the other hand, are slightly different, even though they belong to the family of transcription factors that are similar to *AP2*.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] In addition they are expressed in different ways, although they are very similar in comparison with *PhAP2A*.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] In fact, the mutants for these genes do not show the usual phenotype, that of the null alleles of A genes.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *A. thaliana* the type-B function mainly arises from two genes, *APETALA3* (*AP3*) and *PISTILLATA* (*PI*), both of which are MADS-box genes.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] A mutation of either of these genes causes the homeotic conversion of petals into sepals and of stamens into carpels.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] This also occurs in its orthologs in *A. majus*, which are DEFICIENS (*DEF*) and *GLOBOSA* (*GLO*) respectively.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] For both species the active form of binding with DNA is that derived from the heterodimer: AP3 and PI, or DEF and GLO, dimerize.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] This is the form in which they are able to function.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] The *GLO*/*PI* lines that have been duplicated in *Petunia* contain *P. hybrida GLOBOSA1* (*PhGLO1*, also called *FBP1*) and also *PhGLO2* (also called *PMADS2* or *FBP3*).
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] For the functional elements equivalent to *AP3*/*DEF* in *Petunia* there is both a gene that possesses a relatively similar sequence, called *PhDEF* and there is also an atypical B function gene called PhTM6.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] Phylogenetic studies have placed the first three within the «euAP3» lineage, while PhTM6 belongs to that of «paleoAP3».
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] As discussed above, the floral organs of eudicotyledonous angiosperms are arranged in 4 different verticils, containing the sepals, petals, stamen and carpels.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] The ABC model states that the identity of these organs is determined by the homeotic genes A, A+B, B+C and C, respectively.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] In contrast with the sepal and petal verticils of the eudicots, the perigone of many plants of the family Liliaceae have two nearly identical external petaloid verticils (the tepals).
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] In order to explain the floral morphology of the Liliaceae, van Tunen *et al.* proposed a modified ABC model in 1993.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] This model suggests that class B genes are not only expressed in verticils 2 and 3, but also in 1.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] It therefore follows that the organs of verticils 1 and 2 express class A and B genes and this is how they have a petaloid structure.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] This theoretical model has been experimentally proven through the cloning and characterization of homologs of the *Antirrhinum* genes *GLOBOSA* and *DEFICIENS* in a Liliaceae, the tulip *Tulipa gesneriana*.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] These genes are expressed in verticils 1,2 and 3.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] The homologs *GLOBOSA* and *DEFICIENS* have also been isolated and characterized in *Agapanthus praecox* ssp.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] *orientalis* (Agapanthaceae), which is phylogenetically distant from the model organisms.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] In this study the genes were called *ApGLO* and *ApDEF*, respectively.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] Both contain open reading frames that code for proteins with 210 to 214 amino acids.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] Phylogenetic analysis of these sequences indicated that they belong to B gene family of the monocotyledons.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] In situ hybridization studies revealed that both sequences are expressed in verticil 1 as well as in 2 and 3.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] When taken together, these observations show that the floral development mechanism of *Agapanthus* also follows the modified ABC model.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *A. thaliana*, the C function is derived from one MADS-box type gene called *AGAMOUS* (*AG*), which intervenes both in the establishment of stamen and carpel identity as well as in the determination of the floral meristem.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] Therefore, the *AG* mutants are devoid of androecium and gynoecium and they have petals and sepals in their place.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] In addition, the growth in the centre of the flower is undifferentiated, therefore the petals and sepals grow in repetitive verticils.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] The *PLENA* (*PLE*) gene is present in *A. majus*, in place of the *AG* gene, although it is not an ortholog.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] However, the *FARINELLI* (*FAR*) gene is an ortholog, which is specific to the development of the anthers and the maturation of pollen.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *Petunia*, *Antirrhinum* and in maize the C function is controlled by a number of genes that act in the same manner.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] The genes that are closer homologs of *AG* in *Petunia* are *pMADS3* and *floral-binding protein 6* (*FBP6*).
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] The D function genes were discovered in 1995.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] These genes are MADS-box proteins and they have a function that is distinct from those previously described, although they have a certain homology with C function genes.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] These genes are called *FLORAL BINDING PROTEIN7* (*FBP7*) and *FLORAL BINDING PROTEIN1L* (*FBP1l*).
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] It was found that, in *Petunia*, they are involved in the development of the ovule.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] Equivalent genes were later found in *Arabidopsis*, where they are also involved in controlling the development of carpels and the ovule and even with structures related to seed dispersal.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] The appearance of interesting phenotypes in RNA interference studies in *Petunia* and tomato led, in 1994, to the definition of a new type of function in the floral development model.
[src:botanical-name/abc-model-of-flower-development] The E function was initially thought to be only involved in the development of the three innermost verticils, however, subsequent work found that its expression was required in all the floral verticils.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] The genus name is Neo-Latin, borrowed from Koine Greek ἀκακία (*akakia*), a term used in antiquity to describe a preparation extracted from *Vachellia nilotica*, the original type species.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] Several species of *Acacia* have been introduced to various parts of the world, and two million hectares of commercial plantations have been established.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] Plants in the genus *Acacia* are shrubs or trees with bipinnate leaves, the mature leaves sometimes reduced to phyllodes or rarely absent.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] There are 2 small stipules at the base of the leaf, but sometimes fall off as the leaf matures.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] The flowers are borne in spikes or cylindrical heads, sometimes singly, in pairs or in racemes in the axils of leaves or phyllodes, sometimes in panicles on the ends of branches.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] Each spike or cylindrical head has many small golden-yellow to pale creamy-white flowers, each with 4 or 5 sepals and petals, more than 10 stamens, and a thread-like style that is longer than the stamens.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] The fruit is a variably-shaped pod, sometimes flat or cylindrical, containing seeds with a fleshy aril on the end.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] The genus was first validly named in 1754 by Philip Miller in *The Gardeners Dictionary*.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] In 1913 Nathaniel Lord Britton and Addison Brown selected *Mimosa scorpioides* L.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] (≡ *Acacia scorpioides* (L.) W.Wight = *Acacia nilotica* (L.) Delille), a species from Africa, as the lectotype of the name.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] The genus name comes from Neo-Latin; Gaspard Bauhin in his book *Pinax* (1623) writes it coming from Dioscorides; the Koine term ἀκακία *akakía* is the name he uses for *Vachellia nilotica*, the original type species growing in Roman Egypt, from ἀκακίς *akakis* meaning "point".
[src:botanical-name/acacia] The origin of "wattle" may be an proto-Germanic word meaning "to weave".
[src:botanical-name/acacia] First attested about 700, Old English: *watul* referred to the flexible woody vines, branches, and sticks which were interwoven to form walls, roofs, and fences.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] Since about 1810, it has been used as the common name for the Australian legume trees and shrubs such as *Acacia* species proper, *Castanospermum australe*, and *Sesbania* species that can provide these branches.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] The genus *Acacia* was considered to contain some 1,352 species until 1986.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] In 2003, Pedley published a paper with 834 new combinations in *Racosperma* for species, most of which were formerly placed in *Acacia*.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] All but 10 of these species are native to Australasia, where it constitutes the largest plant genus.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] In the early 2000s, it had become evident that the genus was not monophyletic and that several divergent lineages needed to be placed in separate genera.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] One lineage comprising over 900 species mainly native to Wallacea, Australia, New Guinea, and Indonesia was not closely related to the much smaller African lineage group containing the type species.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] This meant that the Australasian lineage, by far the most prolific in number of species, would need to be renamed.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] This caused controversy between South African and Australian botanists, who both claimed *Acacia* as a symbol of their respective nations and wished to retain the name for their respective branch.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] Pedley's proposed name of *Racosperma* for this group had received little acclaim in the botanical community, especially by Australians.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] In 2003, Anthony Orchard and Bruce Maslin filed a proposal to conserve the name *Acacia* with a different type, to retain the Australasian group of species in the genus *Acacia*.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] Following a controversial decision to choose a new type for *Acacia* in 2005, the Australian component of Acacia sensu lato now retains the name *Acacia*.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] At the 2011 International Botanical Congress held in Melbourne, Australia, the decision to use the name *Acacia*, rather than the proposed *Racosperma* for this genus, was upheld.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] Other Acacia s.l. taxa continue to be called *Acacia* by those considering the entire group as one genus.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] The Australian species of the genus *Paraserianthes* *s.l.* ,namely *P.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] Iophantha*, are deemed its closest relatives.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] The nearest relatives of *Acacia* and *Paraserianthes s.l.* in turn include the Australian and Southeast Asian genera *Archidendron*, *Archidendropsis*, *Pararchidendron* and *Wallaceodendron*, all Mimosoideae.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] The names of more than 1,080 species of *Acacia*, mostly native to Australia, have been accepted by Plants of the World Online as of January 2025.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] An *Acacia*-like 14 cm (5.5 in) long fossil seed pod has been described from the Eocene of the Paris Basin.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] *Acacia*-like fossil pods under the name *Leguminocarpon* are known from late Oligocene deposits at different sites in Hungary.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] Seed pod fossils of †*Acacia parschlugiana* and †*Acacia cyclosperma* are known from Tertiary deposits in Switzerland. †*Acacia colchica* has been described from the Miocene of Georgia west of the Likhi Range.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] Pliocene fossil pollen of an *Acacia* species has been described from western Georgia, including Abkhazia.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] Australia's oldest fossil *Acacia* pollen are recorded from the late Oligocene, 25 million years ago.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] Species of *Acacia* occur in all Australian states and territories, and on its nearby islands.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] About 20 species occur naturally outside Australia and 7 of these also occur in Australia.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] One species (*Acacia koa*) is native to Hawaii and one (*Acacia heterophylla*) is native to Mauritius and Réunion in the Indian Ocean.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] They are present in all terrestrial habitats, including alpine settings, rainforests, woodlands, grasslands, coastal dunes and deserts.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] In drier woodlands or forests they are an important component of the understory.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] Elsewhere they may be dominant, as in the Brigalow Belt, Myall woodlands and the eremaean Mulga woodlands.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] In Australia, *Acacia* forest is the second most common forest type after eucalypt forest, covering 980,000 square kilometres (378,380 sq mi) or 8% of total forest area.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] *Acacia* is also the nation's largest genus of flowering plants with almost 1,000 species found.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] Acacia is a common food source and host plant for butterflies of the genus *Jalmenus.* The imperial hairstreak, *Jalmenus evagoras,* feeds on at least 25 acacia species.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] Many reptiles feed on the sap, such as the native house gecko in Australia.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] The sap is also consumed by bugs (Hemiptera), such as *Hackerobrachys viridiventris* and *Sextius virescens*.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] At least 16 *Acacia* species introduced to South Africa are categorised as invasive.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] In 1847, Acacia species were introduced to stabilise coastal dunes.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] In 1864 *A. mearnsii* was planted for its tannins; it has now become the most widespread invasive alien tree in South Africa.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] Most are classified as highly invasive, Category 1a or 1b invaders.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] This means that most activities with regards to the species are prohibited (such as importing, propagating, introducing, translocating or trading) and it should be ensured that species exempted for an existing plantation does not spread beyond its domain.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] Some species of acacia contain psychoactive alkaloids, and some contain potassium fluoroacetate.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] The seed pods, flowers, and young leaves are generally edible either raw or cooked.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] Aboriginal Australians have traditionally harvested the seeds of some species, to be ground into flour and eaten as a paste or baked into a cake.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] Wattleseeds contain as much as 25% more protein than common cereals, and they store well for long periods due to the hard seed coats.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] In addition to consuming the edible seed and gum, Aboriginal people also employed the timber for implements, weapons, fuel and musical instruments.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] A number of species, most notably *Acacia mangium* (hickory wattle), *A. mearnsii* (black wattle) and *A. saligna* (coojong), are economically important and are widely planted globally for wood products, tannin, firewood and fodder.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] *A. melanoxylon* (blackwood) and *A. aneura* (mulga) supply some of the most attractive timbers in the genus.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] Black wattle bark supported the tanning industries of several countries, and may supply tannins for production of waterproof adhesives.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] In Vietnam, Acacia is used in plantations of non-native species that are regularly clear-cut for paper or timber uses.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] Wattle bark collected in Australia in the 19th century was exported to Europe where it was used in the tanning process.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] One ton of wattle or mimosa bark contained about 68 kilograms (150 pounds) of pure tannin.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] The gum of some species may be used as a substitute for gum arabic, known as Australian gum or wattle gum.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] Some species of acacia – notably *Acacia baileyana*, *A. dealbata* and *A. pravissima* – are cultivated as ornamental garden plants.
[src:botanical-name/acacia] The 1889 publication *Useful Native Plants of Australia* describes various uses for eating.
[src:botanical-name/aestivation-botany] Aestivation can be an important taxonomic diagnostic; for example Malvaceae flower buds have valvate sepals, with the exception of the genera *Fremontodendron* and *Chiranthodendron*, which have sometimes been misplaced as a result.
[src:botanical-name/aestivation-botany] The terms used to describe aestivation are the same as those used to describe leaf vernation.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] The **Agricultural Research Service** (**ARS**) is the principal in-house research agency of the United States Department of Agriculture (USDA).
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] ARS is one of four agencies in USDA's Research, Education and Economics mission area.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] ARS is charged with extending the nation's scientific knowledge and solving agricultural problems through its four national program areas: nutrition, food safety and quality; animal production and protection; natural resources and sustainable agricultural systems; and crop production and protection.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] ARS research focuses on solving problems affecting Americans every day.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] The ARS Headquarters is located in the Jamie L.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] Whitten Building on Independence Avenue in Washington, D.C., and the headquarters staff is located at the George Washington Carver Center (GWCC) in Beltsville, Maryland.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] For 2023, the budget grew to $1.9 billion.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] ARS conducts scientific research for the American public.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] ARS research complements the work of state colleges and universities, agricultural experiment stations, other federal and state agencies, and the private sector.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] ARS research may often focus on regional issues that have national implications, and where there is a clear federal role.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] ARS also provides information on its research results to USDA action and regulatory agencies and to several other federal regulatory agencies, including the Food and Drug Administration and the United States Environmental Protection Agency.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] ARS disseminates much of its research results through scientific journals, technical publications, *Agricultural Research* magazine, and other forums.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] Information is also distributed through ARS's National Agricultural Library (NAL).
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] ARS has more than 150 librarians and other information specialists who work at two NAL locations—the Abraham Lincoln Building in Beltsville, Maryland; and the DC Reference Center in Washington, D.C.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] NAL provides reference and information services, document delivery, interlibrary loan and interlibrary borrowing services to a variety of audiences.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] Prior to the inception of ARS, agricultural research was first conducted under the umbrella of the Agricultural Department in the U.S.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] It was created to collect statistics, distribute seeds and compile and distribute pertinent information.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] In 1862 the USDA was created and agricultural research was moved to its department.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] That same year, the department issued its first research bulletin on the sugar content of grape varietals and their suitability for wine.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] Six years later the USDA would begin its first research on animal diseases, specifically hog cholera, which was causing devastating losses at the time.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] In the early 1900s the USDA began analyzing food composition and the first studies of nutrition and the effects of cooking and processing foods were conducted.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] Finally, in 1953 the Agricultural Research Service was created to be the USDA's primary scientific research agency.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] ARS supports more than 2,000 scientists and post docs working on approximately 690 research projects within 15 National Programs at more than 90 research locations.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] The ARS is divided into 5 geographic areas: Midwest Area, Northeast Area, Pacific West Area, Plains Area, and Southeast Area.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] The research centers focus on innovation in agricultural practices, pest control, health, and nutrition among other things.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] Work at these facilities has given life to numerous products, processes, and technologies.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] Wallace Beltsville Agricultural Research Center (BARC) in Beltsville, Maryland, is the world's largest agricultural research complex.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] Other D.C. area locations include the United States National Agricultural Library and the United States National Arboretum.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] ARS also has six major human nutrition research centers that focus on solving a wide spectrum of human nutrition questions by providing authoritative, peer-reviewed, science-based evidence.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] The centers are located in Arkansas, Maryland, Texas, North Dakota, Massachusetts (the Human Nutrition Research Center on Aging), and California.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] ARS scientists at these centers study the role of food and dietary components in human health from conception to advanced age.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] The ARS also offers the Culture Collection, which is the largest public collection of microorganisms in the world, containing approximately 93,000 strains of bacteria and fungi.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] The ARS Culture Collection is housed at the National Center for Agricultural Utilization Research (NCAUR).
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] There is also a collection of entomopathogenic fungi, called ARSEF, at the Robert W.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] Holley Center for Agriculture and Health in Ithaca, New York.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] Horticultural Research Laboratory in Fort Pierce, Florida, and the U.S.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] National Poultry Research Center in Athens, Georgia.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] Other notable ARS facilities include Northern Great Basin Experimental Range in Oregon, and formerly the Plum Island Animal Disease Center off Long Island.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] Several ARS research units focus on pests, diseases, and management practices of horticultural crops.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] The Cereal Disease Laboratory is located on the campus of the University of Minnesota in Saint Paul.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] It primarily hosts research into rusts and *Fusaria* of cereals.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] The San Joaquin Valley Agricultural Sciences Center in Parlier, California conducts research on specialty crops including grapes, citrus, almonds, alfalfa, peaches, pomegranates, and many others.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] Several research locations throughout the US also house germplasm collections of plant species important for agricultural and industrial uses as part of the **National Genetic Resources Program**.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] From the very beginning the Department of Agriculture and in turn the Agricultural Research Service has been focused on improving not only the farming industry but also the quality of food and the health of Americans.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] In 1985, technology to produce lactose-free milk, yogurt, and ice cream was developed through the Agricultural Research Service.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] The grape breeding program, currently located in Parlier, CA which began in 1923, developed seedless grapes and continues to release new grapevine varieties with improved traits.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] The ARS Citrus and Subtropical Products Laboratory in Winter Haven, Florida, actively works to improve the taste of orange juice concentrate.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] The Agricultural Research Service had a *Toxoplasma gondii* (*T. gondii*) research program, which experimented on cats infected with the parasite, from 1982 until 2018.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] The prevalence of *T. gondii* parasite has been reduced by 50% in the U.S.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] As of September 2018, which the ARS claims is a result of their research.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] The USDA has since discontinued the use of cats in their research amid acute accusations of animal abuse, and a lack of meaningful contribution to the field in recent years (only three of thirteen papers published about *T. gondii* by the ARS were published after the year 2000).
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] More recently, the ARS has focused research on genetics and plant and animal DNA.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] Their research has developed pest-resistant corn, faster growing plants and fish, and a focus on plant and animal genome research and mapping.
[src:botanical-name/agricultural-research-service] Outside of scientific research, the ARS has worked to release databases on food components in order to assist consumers with making informed decisions about food choices.
[src:botanical-name/agronomy] This topic of agronomy involves selective breeding of plants to produce the best crops for various conditions.
[src:botanical-name/agronomy] Plant breeding has increased crop yields and has improved the nutritional value of numerous crops, including corn, soybeans, and wheat.
[src:botanical-name/agronomy] It has also resulted in the development of new types of plants.
[src:botanical-name/agronomy] For example, a hybrid grain named triticale was produced by crossbreeding rye and wheat.
[src:botanical-name/agronomy] Triticale contains more usable protein than does either rye or wheat.
[src:botanical-name/agronomy] Agronomy has also been instrumental for fruit and vegetable production research.
[src:botanical-name/agronomy] Furthermore, the application of plant breeding for turfgrass development has resulted in a reduction in the demand for fertilizer and water inputs (requirements), as well as turf-types with higher disease resistance.
[src:botanical-name/agronomy] Agronomists use biotechnology to extend and expedite the development of desired characteristics.
[src:botanical-name/agronomy] Biotechnology is often a laboratory activity requiring field testing of new crop varieties that are developed.
[src:botanical-name/agronomy] In addition to increasing crop yields agronomic biotechnology is being applied increasingly for novel uses other than food.
[src:botanical-name/agronomy] For example, oilseed is at present used mainly for margarine and other food oils, but it can be modified to produce fatty acids for detergents, substitute fuels and petrochemicals.
[src:botanical-name/agronomy] Agronomists study sustainable ways to make soils more productive and profitable.
[src:botanical-name/agronomy] They classify soils and analyze them to determine whether they contain nutrients vital for plant growth.
[src:botanical-name/agronomy] Common macronutrients analyzed include compounds of nitrogen, phosphorus, potassium, calcium, magnesium, and sulfur.
[src:botanical-name/agronomy] Soil is also assessed for several micronutrients, like zinc and boron.
[src:botanical-name/agronomy] The percentage of organic matter, soil pH, and nutrient holding capacity (cation exchange capacity) are tested in a regional laboratory.
[src:botanical-name/agronomy] Agronomists will interpret these laboratory reports and make recommendations to modify soil nutrients for optimal plant growth.
[src:botanical-name/agronomy] Additionally, agronomists develop methods to preserve soil and decrease the effects of [erosion] by wind and water.
[src:botanical-name/agronomy] For example, a technique known as contour plowing may be used to prevent soil erosion and conserve rainfall.
[src:botanical-name/agronomy] Researchers of agronomy also seek ways to use the soil more effectively for solving other problems.
[src:botanical-name/agronomy] Such problems include the disposal of human and animal manure, water pollution, and pesticide accumulation in the soil, as well as preserving the soil for future generations such as the burning of paddocks after crop production.
[src:botanical-name/agronomy] Pasture management techniques include no-till farming, planting of soil-binding grasses along contours on steep slopes, and using contour drains of depths as much as 1 metre.
[src:botanical-name/agronomy] Agroecology is the management of agricultural systems with an emphasis on ecological and environmental applications.
[src:botanical-name/agronomy] This topic is associated closely with work for sustainable agriculture, organic farming, and alternative food systems and the development of alternative cropping systems.
[src:botanical-name/agronomy] Theoretical production ecology is the quantitative study of the growth of crops.
[src:botanical-name/agronomy] The plant is treated as a kind of biological factory, which processes light, carbon dioxide, water, and nutrients into harvestable products.
[src:botanical-name/agronomy] The main parameters are temperature, sunlight, standing crop biomass, plant production distribution, and nutrient and water supply.
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] The aleurone layer surrounds the endosperm tissue of grass seeds and is morphologically and biochemically distinct from it.
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] Starchy endosperm cells are large, irregularly shaped cells and contain starch grains while aleurone cells are cuboidal in shape and contain aleurone grains.
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] In most cultivated cereals (wheat species, rye, oats, rice and maize) the aleurone is single-layered, whereas barley has a multicellular aleurone layer.
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] Thick primary cell walls enclose and protect the aleurone cells.
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] The aleurone layer is important for both the developing seed and the mature plant.
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] The aleurone tissue accumulates large quantities of oils and lipids that are useful during seed development.
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] It is also a site of mineral storage and in some species, functions in seed dormancy.
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] The aleurone may also express several pathogen-protective proteins including PR-4.
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] Aleurone also serves as the most dietarily beneficial fraction in many brans.
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] In addition, the aleurone tissue contains many protein-storing vacuoles known as protein bodies.
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] In cereals with starchy endosperm, the aleurone contains about 30% of the kernel's proteins.
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] In multicolored corn, anthocyanin pigments in the aleurone layer give the kernels a dark, bluish-black color.
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] Aleurone proteins can have two different morphological features, homogenous and heterogeneous.
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] The homogenous aleurone consists of similar protein bodies (e.g.
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] *Phaseolus vulgaris*) while the heterogeneous aleurone consists of granules of different shapes and types of proteins covered with a membrane (e.g.
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] The development of the aleurone layer involves several periclinal, and anticlinal cell divisions and several steps of genetic regulation.
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] The *dek1* gene and *crinkly4 (cr4)* kinase both function as positive regulators of aleurone cell fate.
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] The normal *dek1* gene is needed in order to receive and respond to positional cues that determine the fate of aleurone cells during development.
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] Mutants of the *dek1* gene block the formation of aleurone and cause the cells to develop as starchy endosperm cells instead of aleurone cells.
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] This causes the seed to lack an aleurone layer.
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] This mutation is caused by the insertion of a *Mu* transposon into the *dek1* gene, causing it to function incorrectly.
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] However, this transposon may sometimes remove itself from the gene, restoring the function of *dek1*.
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] Experiments in this area have helped demonstrate that the cues that determine aleurone positioning are still present in the later stages of development, and the aleurone cells still respond to these cues.
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] Similar to the *dek1* mutation, genes with a mutation in the *cr4* gene also cause a switch in the fate of aleurone cells.
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] The *cr4* gene codes for a receptor kinase and so is involved in signal transduction pathways involving the fate of aleurone cells.
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] Plants with a mutated *cr4* gene are shorter than normal and produce crinkled leaves.
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] In addition, several hormones influence the development of the aleurone layer, including auxin, cytokinin, abscisic acid (ABA), and gibberellin (GA).
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] Auxin and cytokinin play a role in the earlier stages of aleurone development.
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] The maturation of aleurone is promoted by ABA while germination is promoted by GA.
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] The aleurone layer performs a variety of functions to help maintain proper development of the seed.
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] One example of this is maintaining a low pH in the apoplast.
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] In cereals, the aleurone layer releases organic and phosphoric acids in order to keep the pH of the endosperm between a pH of 3.5 and 4.
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] In barley, the aleurone layer also releases nitrite into the starchy endosperm and apoplast under anaerobic conditions.
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] In addition, although the function is unclear, a certain class of hemoglobins is present in the outer layer of living cells including the aleurone tissue in barley and rice seeds.
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] During seed germination, the plant embryo produces the hormone gibberellin which triggers the aleurone cells to release α-amylase for the hydrolysis of starch, proteases, and storage proteins into the endosperm.
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] Evidence that G-proteins play a role in the gibberellin signaling events has been obtained.
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] The breakdown of the starchy endosperm supplies sugars to drive the growth of roots and the acrospire.
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] This release of amylase is considered to be the most important and sole function of the aleurone layer.
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] This effect is inhibited by the plant hormone abscisic acid, which keeps the seed dormant.
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] After completing this function, the aleurone cells in the developing seed undergo apoptosis.
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] Experiments conducted in the 1960s confirmed that in order for the aleurone layer to secrete starch-degrading enzymes, the embryo must be present.
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] Following removal of the embryo, starch-degrading enzymes were not released and no degradation of the starch tissue occurred.
[src:botanical-name/aleurone] The gibberellin effect on the aleurone is used in brewing, specifically in the production of barley malt where treatment ensures that a batch of barley seeds will germinate evenly.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Algae are polyphyletic as they do not share a common ancestor.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Although algae with two-membraned chloroplasts seem to form a paraphyletic group within the clade Archaeplastida, other algae with chloroplasts that have three or more membranes evolved from protists that acquired photosynthesis after engulfing archaeplastids.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Most algae are single-celled organisms without roots, leaves, or stems.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Most are photoautotrophs and the main primary producers of aquatic ecosystems, although some are mixotrophs that derive metabolic energy both from internal photosynthesis and from foraging external nutrients.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Some unicellular algae have become heterotrophs or parasites, relying entirely on external energy sources.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Algae have photosynthetic machinery ultimately derived from cyanobacteria that produce oxygen by splitting water molecules, unlike photosynthetic bacteria.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Fossilized filamentous algae from the Vindhya basin have been dated to 1.6 to 1.7 billion years ago.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Because of the wide range of types of algae, there is a correspondingly wide range of industrial and traditional applications in human society.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Traditional seaweed farming practices have existed for thousands of years and have strong traditions in East Asian food cultures.
[src:botanical-name/algae] More modern algaculture applications extend the food traditions for other applications, including cattle feed, using algae for bioremediation or pollution control, transforming sunlight into algae fuels or other chemicals used in industrial processes, and in medical and scientific applications.
[src:botanical-name/algae] The singular *alga* is the Latin word for "seaweed" and retains that meaning in English.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Although some speculate that it is related to Latin *algēre*, "be cold", no reason is known to associate seaweed with temperature.
[src:botanical-name/algae] A more likely source is *alliga*, "binding, entwining".
[src:botanical-name/algae] The Ancient Greek word for "seaweed" was φῦκος (*phŷkos*), which could mean either the seaweed (probably red algae) or a red dye derived from it.
[src:botanical-name/algae] The Latinization, *fūcus*, meant primarily the cosmetic rouge.
[src:botanical-name/algae] The etymology is uncertain, but a strong candidate has long been some word related to the Biblical פוך (*pūk*), "paint" (if not that word itself), a cosmetic eye-shadow used by the Ancient Egyptians and other inhabitants of the eastern Mediterranean.
[src:botanical-name/algae] It could be any color: black, red, green, or blue.
[src:botanical-name/algae] The study of algae is most commonly called phycology (from Greek *phykos* 'seaweed'); the term algology is falling out of use.
[src:botanical-name/algae] The algae are a heterogeneous group of mostly photosynthetic organisms that produce oxygen and lack the reproductive features and structural complexity of land plants.
[src:botanical-name/algae] This concept includes the cyanobacteria, which are prokaryotes, and all photosynthetic protists, which are eukaryotes.
[src:botanical-name/algae] They contain chlorophyll *a* as their primary photosynthetic pigment, and generally inhabit aquatic environments.
[src:botanical-name/algae] However, there are many exceptions to this definition.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Many non-photosynthetic protists are included in the study of algae, such as the heterotrophic relatives of euglenophytes or the numerous species of colorless algae that have lost their chlorophyll during evolution (e.g., *Prototheca*).
[src:botanical-name/algae] Some exceptional species of algae tolerate dry terrestrial habitats, such as soil, rocks, or caves hidden from light sources, although they still need enough moisture to become active.
[src:botanical-name/algae] A range of algal morphologies is exhibited, and convergence of features in unrelated groups is common.
[src:botanical-name/algae] The only groups to exhibit three-dimensional multicellular thalli are the reds and browns, and some chlorophytes.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Apical growth is constrained to subsets of these groups: the florideophyte reds, various browns, and the charophytes.
[src:botanical-name/algae] The form of charophytes is quite different from those of reds and browns, because they have distinct nodes, separated by internode 'stems'; whorls of branches reminiscent of the horsetails occur at the nodes.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Conceptacles are another polyphyletic trait; they appear in the coralline algae and the Hildenbrandiales, as well as the browns.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Most of the simpler algae are unicellular flagellates or amoeboids, but colonial and nonmotile forms have developed independently among several of the groups.
[src:botanical-name/algae] In three lines, even higher levels of organization have been reached, with full tissue differentiation.
[src:botanical-name/algae] These are the brown algae,—some of which may reach 50 m in length (kelps)—the red algae, and the green algae.
[src:botanical-name/algae] The most complex forms are found among the charophyte algae (see Charales and Charophyta), in a lineage that eventually led to the higher land plants.
[src:botanical-name/algae] The innovation that defines these nonalgal plants is the presence of female reproductive organs with protective cell layers that protect the zygote and developing embryo.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Hence, the land plants are referred to as the Embryophytes.
[src:botanical-name/algae] The term algal turf is commonly used but poorly defined.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Algal turfs are thick, carpet-like beds of seaweed that retain sediment and compete with foundation species like corals and kelps, and they are usually less than 15 cm tall.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Such a turf may consist of one or more species, and will generally cover an area in the order of a square metre or more.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Many algae, particularly species of the Characeae, have served as model experimental organisms to understand the mechanisms of the water permeability of membranes, osmoregulation, salt tolerance, cytoplasmic streaming, and the generation of action potentials.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Plant hormones are found not only in higher plants, but in algae, too.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Rhodophyta, Chlorophyta, and Heterokontophyta, the three main algal divisions, have life cycles which show considerable variation and complexity.
[src:botanical-name/algae] In general, an asexual phase exists where the seaweed's cells are diploid, a sexual phase where the cells are haploid, followed by fusion of the male and female gametes.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Asexual reproduction permits efficient population increases, but less variation is possible.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Commonly, in sexual reproduction of unicellular and colonial algae, two specialized, sexually compatible, haploid gametes make physical contact and fuse to form a zygote.
[src:botanical-name/algae] To ensure a successful mating, the development and release of gametes is highly synchronized and regulated; pheromones may play a key role in these processes.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Sexual reproduction allows for more variation and provides the benefit of efficient recombinational repair of DNA damage during meiosis, a key stage of the sexual cycle.
[src:botanical-name/algae] However, sexual reproduction is more costly than asexual reproduction.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Meiosis has been shown to occur in many different species of algae.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Linnaeus, in *Species Plantarum* (1753), the starting point for modern botanical nomenclature, recognized 14 genera of algae, of which only four are currently considered among algae.
[src:botanical-name/algae] In *Systema Naturae*, Linnaeus described the genera *Volvox* and *Corallina*, and a species of *Acetabularia* (as *Madrepora*), among the animals.
[src:botanical-name/algae] In 1768, Samuel Gottlieb Gmelin (1744–1774) published the *Historia Fucorum*, the first work dedicated to marine algae and the first book on marine biology to use the then new binomial nomenclature of Linnaeus.
[src:botanical-name/algae] It included elaborate illustrations of seaweed and marine algae on folded leaves.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Harvey (1811–1866) and Lamouroux (1813) were the first to divide macroscopic algae into four divisions based on their pigmentation.
[src:botanical-name/algae] This is the first use of a biochemical criterion in plant systematics.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Harvey's four divisions are: red algae (Rhodospermae), brown algae (Melanospermae), green algae (Chlorospermae), and Diatomaceae.
[src:botanical-name/algae] At this time, microscopic algae were discovered and reported by a different group of workers (e.g., O.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Müller and Ehrenberg) studying the Infusoria (microscopic organisms).
[src:botanical-name/algae] Unlike macroalgae, which were clearly viewed as plants, microalgae were frequently considered animals because they are often motile.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Even the nonmotile (coccoid) microalgae were sometimes merely seen as stages of the lifecycle of plants, macroalgae, or animals.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Although used as a taxonomic category in some pre-Darwinian classifications, e.g., Linnaeus (1753), de Jussieu (1789), Lamouroux (1813), Harvey (1836), Horaninow (1843), Agassiz (1859), Wilson & Cassin (1864), in further classifications, the "algae" are seen as an artificial, polyphyletic group.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Throughout the 20th century, most classifications treated the following groups as divisions or classes of algae: cyanophytes, rhodophytes, chrysophytes, xanthophytes, bacillariophytes, phaeophytes, pyrrhophytes (cryptophytes and dinophytes), euglenophytes, and chlorophytes.
[src:botanical-name/algae] With the abandonment of plant-animal dichotomous classification, most groups of algae (sometimes all) were included in Protista, later also abandoned in favour of Eukaryota.
[src:botanical-name/algae] However, as a legacy of the older plant life scheme, some groups that were also treated as protozoans in the past still have duplicated classifications (see ambiregnal protists).
[src:botanical-name/algae] In other cases, some groups were originally characterized as parasitic algae (e.g., *Chlorochytrium*), but later were seen as endophytic algae.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Some filamentous bacteria (e.g., *Beggiatoa*) were originally seen as algae.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Furthermore, groups like the apicomplexans are also parasites derived from ancestors that possessed plastids, but are not included in any group traditionally seen as algae.
[src:botanical-name/algae] The most recent estimate (as of January 2024) documents 50,605 living and 10,556 fossil algal species, according to the online database AlgaeBase.
[src:botanical-name/algae] They are classified into 15 phyla or divisions.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Some phyla are not photosynthetic, namely Picophyta and Rhodelphidophyta, but they are included in the database due to their close relationship with red algae.
[src:botanical-name/algae] The various algal phyla can be differentiated according to several biological traits.
[src:botanical-name/algae] They have distinct morphologies, photosynthetic pigmentation, storage products, cell wall composition, and mechanisms of carbon concentration.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Some phyla have unique cellular structures.
[src:botanical-name/algae] , the most common genus of cyanobacteria.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Among prokaryotes, five major groups of bacteria have evolved the ability to photosynthesize, including heliobacteria, green sulfur and nonsulfur bacteria and proteobacteria.
[src:botanical-name/algae] However, the only lineage where oxygenic photosynthesis has evolved is in the cyanobacteria, often known as blue-green algae for their blue-green (cyan) coloration.
[src:botanical-name/algae] They are classified as the phylum Cyanobacteriota or Cyanophyta.
[src:botanical-name/algae] However, this phylum also includes two classes of non-photosynthetic bacteria: Melainabacteria (also called Vampirovibrionia or Vampirovibrionophyceae) and Sericytochromatia (also known as Blackallbacteria).
[src:botanical-name/algae] A third class contains the photosynthetic ones, known as Cyanophyceae (also called Cyanobacteriia or Oxyphotobacteria).
[src:botanical-name/algae] As bacteria, their cells lack membrane-bound organelles, with the exception of thylakoids.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Like other algae, cyanobacteria have chlorophyll *a* as their primary photosynthetic pigment.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Their accessory pigments include phycobilins (phycoerythrobilin and phycocyanobilin), carotenoids and, in some cases, *b*, *d*, or *f* chlorophylls, generally distributed in phycobilisomes found in the surface of thylakoids.
[src:botanical-name/algae] They display a variety of body forms, such as single cells, colonies, and unbranched or branched filaments.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Their cells are commonly covered in a sheath of mucilage, and they also have a typical gram-negative bacterial cell wall composed largely of peptidoglycan.
[src:botanical-name/algae] They have various storage particles, including cyanophycin as aminoacid and nitrogen reserves, "cyanophycean starch" (similar to plant amylose) for carbohydrates, and lipid droplets.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Their Rubisco enzymes are concentrated in carboxysomes.
[src:botanical-name/algae] They occupy a diverse array of aquatic and terrestrial habitats, including extreme environments from hot springs to polar glaciers.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Some are subterranean, living via hydrogen-based lithoautotrophy instead of photosynthesis.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Three lineages of cyanobacteria, *Prochloraceae*, *Prochlorothrix* and *Prochlorococcus*, independently evolved to have chlorophylls *a* and *b* instead of phycobilisomes.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Due to their different pigmentation, they were historically grouped in a separate division, Prochlorophyta, as this is the typical pigmentation seen in green algae (e.g., chlorophytes).
[src:botanical-name/algae] Eventually, this classification became obsolete, as it is a polyphyletic grouping.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Cyanobacteria are included as algae by most phycological sources and by the International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants, although a few authors exclude them from the definition of algae and reserve the term for eukaryotes only.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Eukaryotic algae contain chloroplasts that are similar in structure to cyanobacteria.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Chloroplasts contain circular DNA like that in cyanobacteria and are interpreted as representing reduced endosymbiotic cyanobacteria.
[src:botanical-name/algae] However, the exact origin of the chloroplasts is different among separate lineages of algae, reflecting their acquisition during different endosymbiotic events.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Many groups contain some members that are no longer photosynthetic.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Some retain plastids, but not chloroplasts, while others have lost plastids entirely.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Primary algae are those with "primary chloroplasts", i.e. chloroplasts with two membranes, evolved through a single symbiogenetic event with an endosymbiont β-cyanobacterium as early as 1.6 Gya during the Mesoproterozoic.
[src:botanical-name/algae] These algae are mainly grouped in the clade Archaeplastida (meaning "ancient plastid"), which includes the major groups Viridiplantae (green algae *sensu lato* and all land plants) and Rhodophyta (red algae) as well as the minor group Glaucophyta (grey algae).
[src:botanical-name/algae] Land plants (embryophytes) are pigmented similarly to green algae and likely evolved from the freshwater green algae clade Streptophyta, which is sister taxon to Chlorophyta (green algae *sensu stricto*) and the basal clade Prasinodermophyta.
[src:botanical-name/algae] There is also a minor group of amoeboid protists with primary plastids evolved via different origin and at a much later date than archaeplastid chloroplasts.
[src:botanical-name/algae] The four species of the euglyphid amoebae genus *Paulinella*, have cyanobionts (known as cyanelles) that perform photosynthesis, likely originated from the endosymbiosis of a α-cyanobacterium (probably an ancestral member of Chroococcales), about 90–140 Mya during the Cretaceous.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Secondary algae are eukaryotes with "secondary chloroplasts", i.e. those evolved from phagocytosis and subsequent endosymbiosis of primary algae (mainly green or red algae) or other secondary algae, thus "stealing" the endosymbionts' photosynthetic capability.
[src:botanical-name/algae] As a result, these algae have chloroplasts surrounded by three or more membranes, and appeared independently in various distantly related protist lineages.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Two lineages of secondary algae, chlorarachniophytes and euglenophytes have "green" chloroplasts containing chlorophylls *a* and *b*.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Their chloroplasts are surrounded by four and three membranes, respectively, and were probably retained from ingested green algae.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Other groups have "red" chloroplasts containing chlorophylls *a* and *c*, and phycobilins.
[src:botanical-name/algae] The shape can vary; they may be of discoid, plate-like, reticulate, cup-shaped, spiral, or ribbon shaped.
[src:botanical-name/algae] They have one or more pyrenoids to preserve protein and starch.
[src:botanical-name/algae] The latter chlorophyll type is not known from any prokaryotes or primary chloroplasts, but genetic similarities with red algae suggest a relationship there.
[src:botanical-name/algae] The typical dinoflagellate chloroplast has three membranes, but considerable diversity exists in chloroplasts within the group, and a number of endosymbiotic events apparently occurred.
[src:botanical-name/algae] The Apicomplexa, a group of closely related parasites, also have plastids called apicoplasts, which are not photosynthetic.
[src:botanical-name/algae] The Chromerida are the closest relatives of apicomplexans, and some have retained their chloroplasts.
[src:botanical-name/algae] The three alveolate groups evolved from a common myzozoan ancestor that obtained chloroplasts.
[src:botanical-name/algae] The distribution of algal species has been fairly well studied since the founding of phytogeography in the mid-19th century.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Algae spread mainly by the dispersal of spores analogously to the dispersal of cryptogamic plants by spores.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Spores can be found in a variety of environments: fresh and marine waters, air, soil, and in or on other organisms.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Whether a spore is to grow into an adult organism depends on the species and the environmental conditions where the spore lands.
[src:botanical-name/algae] The spores of freshwater algae are dispersed mainly by running water and wind, as well as by living carriers.
[src:botanical-name/algae] However, not all bodies of water can carry all species of algae, as the chemical composition of certain water bodies limits the algae that can survive within them.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Marine spores are often spread by ocean currents.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Ocean water presents many vastly different habitats based on temperature and nutrient availability, resulting in phytogeographic zones, regions, and provinces.
[src:botanical-name/algae] To some degree, the distribution of algae is subject to floristic discontinuities caused by geographical features, such as Antarctica, long distances of ocean or general land masses.
[src:botanical-name/algae] It is, therefore, possible to identify species occurring by locality, such as "Pacific algae" or "North Sea algae".
[src:botanical-name/algae] When they occur out of their localities, hypothesizing a transport mechanism is usually possible, such as the hulls of ships.
[src:botanical-name/algae] For example, *Ulva reticulata* and *U. fasciata* travelled from the mainland to Hawaii in this manner.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Mapping is possible for select species only: "there are many valid examples of confined distribution patterns." For example, *Clathromorphum* is an arctic genus and is not mapped far south of there.
[src:botanical-name/algae] For example, according to one standard textbook, in the British Isles, the *UK Biodiversity Steering Group Report* estimated there to be 20,000 algal species in the UK.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Another checklist reports only about 5,000 species.
[src:botanical-name/algae] and so on, but lacking any scientific basis or reliable sources, these numbers have no more credibility than the British ones mentioned above.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Most estimates also omit microscopic algae, such as phytoplankton.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Algae are prominent in bodies of water, common in terrestrial environments, and are found in unusual environments, such as on snow and ice.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Seaweeds grow mostly in shallow marine waters, less than 100 m (330 ft) deep; however, some such as *Navicula pennata* have been recorded to a depth of 360 m (1,180 ft).
[src:botanical-name/algae] A type of algae, *Ancylonema nordenskioeldii*, was found in Greenland in areas known as the 'Dark Zone', which caused an increase in the rate of melting ice sheet.
[src:botanical-name/algae] The same algae was found in the Italian Alps, after pink ice appeared on parts of the Presena glacier.
[src:botanical-name/algae] The various sorts of algae play significant roles in aquatic ecology.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Microscopic forms that live suspended in the water column (phytoplankton) provide the food base for most marine food chains.
[src:botanical-name/algae] In very high densities (algal blooms), these algae may discolor the water and outcompete, poison, or asphyxiate other life forms.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Algae can be used as indicator organisms to monitor pollution in various aquatic systems.
[src:botanical-name/algae] In many cases, algal metabolism is sensitive to various pollutants.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Due to this, the species composition of algal populations may shift in the presence of chemical pollutants.
[src:botanical-name/algae] To detect these changes, algae can be sampled from the environment and maintained in laboratories with relative ease.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Some species of algae form symbiotic relationships with other organisms.
[src:botanical-name/algae] In these symbioses, the algae supply photosynthates (organic substances) to the host organism providing protection to the algal cells.
[src:botanical-name/algae] The host organism derives some or all of its energy requirements from the algae.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Lichens are defined by the International Association for Lichenology to be "an association of a fungus and a photosynthetic symbiont resulting in a stable vegetative body having a specific structure".
[src:botanical-name/algae] The fungi, or mycobionts, are mainly from the Ascomycota with a few from the Basidiomycota.
[src:botanical-name/algae] In nature, they do not occur separate from lichens.
[src:botanical-name/algae] It is unknown when they began to associate.
[src:botanical-name/algae] One or more mycobiont associates with the same phycobiont species, from the green algae, except that alternatively, the mycobiont may associate with a species of cyanobacteria (hence "photobiont" is the more accurate term).
[src:botanical-name/algae] A photobiont may be associated with many different mycobionts or may live independently; accordingly, lichens are named and classified as fungal species.
[src:botanical-name/algae] The association is termed a morphogenesis because the lichen has a form and capabilities not possessed by the symbiont species alone (they can be experimentally isolated).
[src:botanical-name/algae] The photobiont possibly triggers otherwise latent genes in the mycobiont.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Trentepohlia is an example of a common green alga genus worldwide that can grow on its own or be lichenised.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Lichen thus share some of the habitat and often similar appearance with specialized species of algae (*aerophytes*) growing on exposed surfaces such as tree trunks and rocks and sometimes discoloring them.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Coral reefs are accumulated from the calcareous exoskeletons of marine invertebrates of the order Scleractinia (stony corals).
[src:botanical-name/algae] These animals metabolize sugar and oxygen to obtain energy for their cell-building processes, including secretion of the exoskeleton, with water and carbon dioxide as byproducts.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Dinoflagellates (algal protists) are often endosymbionts in the cells of the coral-forming marine invertebrates, where they accelerate host-cell metabolism by generating sugar and oxygen immediately available through photosynthesis using incident light and the carbon dioxide produced by the host.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Reef-building stony corals (hermatypic corals) require endosymbiotic algae from the genus *Symbiodinium* to be in a healthy condition.
[src:botanical-name/algae] The loss of *Symbiodinium* from the host is known as coral bleaching, a condition which leads to the deterioration of a reef.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Endosymbiontic green algae live close to the surface of some sponges, for example, breadcrumb sponges (*Halichondria panicea*).
[src:botanical-name/algae] The alga is thus protected from predators; the sponge is provided with oxygen and sugars which can account for 50 to 80% of sponge growth in some species.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Prokaryotic algae, i.e., cyanobacteria, are the only group of organisms where oxygenic photosynthesis has evolved.
[src:botanical-name/algae] The oldest undisputed fossil evidence of cyanobacteria is dated at 2100 million years ago, although stromatolites, associated with cyanobacterial biofilms, appear as early as 3500 million years ago in the fossil record.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Eukaryotic algae are polyphyletic thus their origin cannot be traced back to a single hypothetical common ancestor.
[src:botanical-name/algae] It is thought that they came into existence when photosynthetic coccoid cyanobacteria got phagocytized by a unicellular heterotrophic eukaryote (a protist), giving rise to double-membranous primary plastids.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Such symbiogenic events (primary symbiogenesis) are believed to have occurred more than 1.5 billion years ago during the Calymmian period, early in Boring Billion, but it is difficult to track the key events because of so much time gap.
[src:botanical-name/algae] This process of serial cell "capture" and "enslavement" explains the diversity of photosynthetic eukaryotes.
[src:botanical-name/algae] The oldest undisputed fossil evidence of eukaryotic algae is *Bangiomorpha pubescens*, a red alga found in rocks around 1047 million years old.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Recent genomic and phylogenomic approaches have significantly clarified plastid genome evolution, the horizontal movement of endosymbiont genes to the "host" nuclear genome, and plastid spread throughout the eukaryotic tree of life.
[src:botanical-name/algae] It is accepted that both euglenophytes and chlorarachniophytes obtained their chloroplasts from chlorophytes that became endosymbionts.
[src:botanical-name/algae] In particular, euglenophyte chloroplasts share the most resemblance with the genus *Pyramimonas*.
[src:botanical-name/algae] However, there is still no clear order in which the secondary and tertiary endosymbioses occurred for the "chromist" lineages (ochrophytes, cryptophytes, haptophytes and myzozoans).
[src:botanical-name/algae] Two main models have been proposed to explain the order, both of which agree that cryptophytes obtained their chloroplasts from red algae.
[src:botanical-name/algae] One model, hypothesized in 2014 by John W.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Stiller and coauthors, suggests that a cryptophyte became the plastid of ochrophytes, which in turn became the plastid of myzozoans and haptophytes.
[src:botanical-name/algae] The other model, suggested by Andrzej Bodył and coauthors in 2009, describes that a cryptophyte became the plastid of both haptophytes and ochrophytes, and it is a haptophyte that became the plastid of myzozoans instead.
[src:botanical-name/algae] These charophyte algae probably already developed filamentous thalli and holdfasts that superficially resembled plant stems and roots, and probably had an isomorphic alternation of generations.
[src:botanical-name/algae] They perhaps evolved some 850 mya and might even be as early as 1 Gya during the late phase of the Boring Billion.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Algaculture is a form of aquaculture involving the farming of species of algae.
[src:botanical-name/algae] The majority of algae that are intentionally cultivated fall into the category of microalgae (also referred to as phytoplankton, microphytes, or planktonic algae).
[src:botanical-name/algae] Global production of farmed aquatic plants, overwhelmingly dominated by seaweeds, grew in output volume from 13.5 million tonnes in 1995, to just over 30 million tonnes in 2016 and 37.8 million tonnes in 2022 and 40 million tonnes in 2024.
[src:botanical-name/algae] This increase was the result of production expansions led by China, followed by Malaysia, the Philippines, the United Republic of Tanzania, and the Russian Federation.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Cultured microalgae already contribute to a wide range of sectors in the emerging bioeconomy.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Research suggests there are large potentials and benefits of algaculture for the development of a future healthy and sustainable food system.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Seaweed farming or kelp farming is the practice of cultivating and harvesting seaweed.
[src:botanical-name/algae] In its simplest form farmers gather from natural beds, while at the other extreme farmers fully control the crop's life cycle.
[src:botanical-name/algae] The seven most cultivated taxa are *Eucheuma* spp., *Kappaphycus alvarezii*, *Gracilaria* spp., *Saccharina japonica*, *Undaria pinnatifida*, *Pyropia* spp., and *Sargassum fusiforme*.
[src:botanical-name/algae] *Eucheuma* and *K. alvarezii* are attractive for carrageenan (a gelling agent); *Gracilaria* is farmed for agar; the rest are eaten after limited processing.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Seaweeds are different from mangroves and seagrasses, as they are photosynthetic algal organisms and are non-flowering.
[src:botanical-name/algae] The largest seaweed-producing countries as of 2022 are China (58.62%) and Indonesia (28.6%); followed by South Korea (5.09%) and the Philippines (4.19%).
[src:botanical-name/algae] Seaweed farming has frequently been developed to improve economic conditions and to reduce fishing pressure.
[src:botanical-name/algae] The Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) reported that world production in 2019 was over 35 million tonnes.
[src:botanical-name/algae] North America produced some 23,000 tonnes of wet seaweed.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Alaska, Maine, France, and Norway each more than doubled their seaweed production since 2018*.* As of 2019, seaweed represented 30% of marine aquaculture.
[src:botanical-name/algae] In 2023, the global seaweed extract market was valued at $16.5 billion, with strong projected growth.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Seaweed farming is a carbon negative crop, with a high potential for climate change mitigation.
[src:botanical-name/algae] The IPCC Special Report on the Ocean and Cryosphere in a Changing Climate recommends "further research attention" as a mitigation tactic.
[src:botanical-name/algae] World Wildlife Fund, Oceans 2050, and The Nature Conservancy publicly support expanded seaweed cultivation.
[src:botanical-name/algae] An algae bioreactor is used for cultivating micro or macroalgae.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Algae may be cultivated for the purposes of biomass production (as in a seaweed cultivator), wastewater treatment, CO2 fixation, or aquarium/pond filtration in the form of an algae scrubber.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Algae bioreactors vary widely in design, falling broadly into two categories: open reactors and enclosed reactors.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Open reactors are exposed to the atmosphere while enclosed reactors, also commonly called photobioreactors, are isolated to varying extents from the atmosphere.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Specifically, algae bioreactors can be used to produce fuels such as biodiesel and bioethanol, to generate animal feed, or to reduce pollutants such as NOx and CO2 in flue gases of power plants.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Fundamentally, this kind of bioreactor is based on the photosynthetic reaction, which is performed by the chlorophyll-containing algae itself using dissolved carbon dioxide and sunlight.
[src:botanical-name/algae] The carbon dioxide is dispersed into the reactor fluid to make it accessible to the algae.
[src:botanical-name/algae] The bioreactor has to be made out of transparent material.
[src:botanical-name/algae] To be competitive and independent from fluctuating support from (local) policy on the long run, biofuels should equal or beat the cost level of fossil fuels.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Here, algae-based fuels hold great promise, directly related to the potential to produce more biomass per unit area in a year than any other form of biomass.
[src:botanical-name/algae] The break-even point for algae-based biofuels is estimated to occur by 2025.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Today, algae are used by humans in many ways; for example, as fertilizers, soil conditioners, and livestock feed.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Aquatic and microscopic species are cultured in clear tanks or ponds and are either harvested or used to treat effluents pumped through the ponds.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Algaculture on a large scale is an important type of aquaculture in some places.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Maerl is commonly used as a soil conditioner.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Algae are used as foods in many countries: China consumes more than 70 species, including *fat choy*, a cyanobacterium considered a vegetable; Japan, over 20 species such as *nori* and *aonori*; Ireland, dulse; Chile, cochayuyo.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Laver is used to make laverbread in Wales, where it is known as *bara lawr*.
[src:botanical-name/algae] In Korea, green laver is used to make *gim*.
[src:botanical-name/algae] The oils from some algae have high levels of unsaturated fatty acids.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Some varieties of algae favored by vegetarianism and veganism contain the long-chain, essential omega-3 fatty acids, docosahexaenoic acid (DHA) and eicosapentaenoic acid (EPA).
[src:botanical-name/algae] Fish oil contains the omega-3 fatty acids, but the original source is algae (microalgae in particular), which are eaten by marine life such as copepods and are passed up the food chain.
[src:botanical-name/algae] The natural pigments (carotenoids and chlorophylls) produced by algae can be used as alternatives to chemical dyes and coloring agents.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Carrageenan, from the red alga *Chondrus crispus*, is used as a thickener and stabilizer in milk products.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Agar, a gelatinous substance derived from red algae, has a number of commercial uses.
[src:botanical-name/algae] It is a good medium on which to grow bacteria and fungi, as most microorganisms cannot digest agar.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Alginic acid, or alginate, is extracted from brown algae.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Its uses range from gelling agents in food, to medical dressings.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Alginic acid also has been used in the field of biotechnology as a biocompatible medium for cell encapsulation and cell immobilization.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Molecular cuisine is also a user of the substance for its gelling properties, by which it becomes a delivery vehicle for flavours.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Between 100,000 and 170,000 wet tons of *Macrocystis* are harvested annually in New Mexico for alginate extraction and abalone feed.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Agricultural Research Service scientists found that 60–90% of nitrogen runoff and 70–100% of phosphorus runoff can be captured from manure effluents using a horizontal algae scrubber, also called an algal turf scrubber (ATS).
[src:botanical-name/algae] Scientists developed the ATS, which consists of shallow, 30-metre (100 ft) raceways of nylon netting where algae colonies can form, and studied its efficacy for three years.
[src:botanical-name/algae] They found that algae can readily be used to reduce the nutrient runoff from agricultural fields and increase the quality of water flowing into rivers, streams, and oceans.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Researchers collected and dried the nutrient-rich algae from the ATS and studied its potential as an organic fertilizer.
[src:botanical-name/algae] They found that cucumber and corn seedlings grew just as well using ATS organic fertilizer as they did with commercial fertilizers.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Algae scrubbers, using bubbling upflow or vertical waterfall versions, are now also being used to filter aquaria and ponds.
[src:botanical-name/algae] The alga *Stichococcus bacillaris* has been seen to colonize silicone resins used at archaeological sites; biodegrading the synthetic substance.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Various polymers can be created from algae, which can be especially useful in the creation of bioplastics.
[src:botanical-name/algae] These include hybrid plastics, cellulose-based plastics, poly-lactic acid, and bio-polyethylene.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Several companies have begun to produce algae polymers commercially, including for use in flip-flops and in surf boards.
[src:botanical-name/algae] Even algae is also used to prepare various polymeric resins suitable for coating applications.
[src:botanical-name/algae] The third island on Kunming Lake at Beijing's Summer Palace is called Zaojian Tang Dao (藻鑒堂島).
[src:botanical-name/botanical-name] The purpose of a formal name is to have a single name that is accepted and used worldwide for a particular plant or plant group.
[src:botanical-name/botanical-name] For example, the botanical name *Bellis perennis* denotes a plant species which is native to most of the countries of Europe and the Middle East, where it has accumulated various names in many languages.
[src:botanical-name/botanical-name] Later, the plant was introduced worldwide, bringing it into contact with more languages.
[src:botanical-name/botanical-name] English names for this plant species include: daisy, English daisy, and lawn daisy.
[src:botanical-name/botanical-name] The cultivar *Bellis perennis* 'Aucubifolia' is a golden-variegated horticultural selection of this species.
[src:botanical-name/botanical-name] The botanical name itself is fixed by a type, which is a particular specimen (or in some cases a group of specimens) of an organism to which the scientific name is formally attached.
[src:botanical-name/botanical-name] In other words, a type is an example that serves to anchor or centralize the defining features of that particular taxon.
[src:botanical-name/botanical-name] For example, the traditional view of the family Malvaceae has been expanded in some modern approaches to include what were formerly considered to be several closely related families.
[src:botanical-name/botanical-name] Some botanical names refer to groups that are very stable (for example Equisetaceae, Magnoliaceae) while for other names a careful check is needed to see which circumscription is being used (for example Fabaceae, Amygdaloideae, *Taraxacum officinale*).
[src:botanical-name/botanical-name] Depending on rank, botanical names may be in one part (genus and above), two parts (various situations below the rank of genus) or three parts (below the rank of species).
[src:botanical-name/botanical-name] The names of cultivated plants are not necessarily similar to the botanical names, since they may instead involve "unambiguous common names" of species or genera.
[src:botanical-name/botanical-name] apart from cultivars, the name of a plant can never have more than three parts.
[src:botanical-name/botanical-name] A botanical name in three parts, i.e., an infraspecific name (a name for a taxon below the rank of species) needs a "connecting term" to indicate rank.
[src:botanical-name/botanical-name] In the *Calystegia* example above, this is "subsp.", an abbreviation for subspecies.
[src:botanical-name/botanical-name] In botany there are many ranks below that of species (in zoology there is only one such rank, subspecies, so that this "connecting term" is not used in zoology).
[src:botanical-name/botanical-name] A name of a "subdivision of a genus" also needs a connecting term (in the *Acacia* example above, this is "subg.", an abbreviation for subgenus).
[src:botanical-name/botanical-name] The connecting term is not part of the name itself.
[src:botanical-name/botanical-name] A taxon may be indicated by a listing in more than three parts: "*Saxifraga aizoon* var.
[src:botanical-name/botanical-name] *surculosa* Engl. & Irmsch." but this is a classification, not a formal botanical name.
[src:botanical-name/botanical-name] The botanical name is *Saxifraga aizoon* subf.
[src:botanical-name/botanical-name] Generic, specific, and infraspecific botanical names are usually printed in italics.
[src:botanical-name/botanical-name] The example set by the *ICN* is to italicize all botanical names, including those above genus, though the *ICN* preface states: "The *Code* sets no binding standard in this respect, as typography is a matter of editorial style and tradition not of nomenclature".
[src:botanical-name/botanical-name] For botanical nomenclature, the *ICN* prescribes a two-part name or **binary name** for any taxon below the rank of genus down to, and including, the rank of species.
[src:botanical-name/botanical-name] Taxa below the rank of species get a three part (infraspecific name).
[src:botanical-name/botanical-name] A binary name consists of the name of a genus and an epithet.
[src:botanical-name/botanical-name] There is no connecting term involved to indicate the rank.
[src:botanical-name/botanical-name] In the case of cultivated plants, there is an additional epithet which is an often non-Latin part, not written in italics.
[src:botanical-name/botanical-name] For cultivars, it is always given in single quotation marks.
[src:botanical-name/botanical-name] The cultivar, Group, or grex epithet may follow either the botanical name of the species, or the name of the genus only, or the unambiguous common name of the genus or species.
[src:botanical-name/botanical-name] The generic name, followed by a cultivar name, is often used when the parentage of a particular hybrid cultivar is not relevant in the context, or is uncertain.
